{
  "texts": [
    "This Perspective focuses on these emerging opportunities and challenges centered around optical computing in free-space.",
    "We expect the comparatively analyzed methodologies in this Perspective to profoundly impact the next-generation wave-based free-space computing technologies ranging from all-optical statistical inference and computational imaging to wireless communications, edge computing, and others.",
    "Diffractive surfaces A diffractive surface-based free-space optical processor is spatially engineered at the wavelength scale (λ/2 or larger) to generate a desired spatial distribution of the complex-valued light transmission/reflection coefficients (Fig. 3a, b, Supplementary Fig.",
    "Unlike standard refractive optical components, e.g., lenses, such diffractive surfaces are pixelated in 2D, and their structure contains physical thickness and/or transmission discontinuities with a lateral period of ≥λ/2; also see Supplementary Discussion 1.",
    "The structure of these variations along the optical axis is typically on the order of the wavelength of the propagating light, and therefore, they can, in general, be modeled as 2D thin optical elements."
  ]
}